Whether or not the hospitalizations in Texas will decline below 2,500 soon/before 04 October 2020 will depend on whether one assumes that the relatively stationary values of 12 to 15 September 2020 are a short hiatus in the decline/a transient outlier, or whether they are part of a new plateau which will be hard to come below, as some forecasters suggest.

Week over week cases have increased for three consecutive days. We could be reaching the plateau in cases. It's a little difficult to understand the impact of this on hospitalizations since the change in current hospitalizations can be very roughly approximately by new cases 1 week ago minus new cases 3 weeks ago--this means that hospitalizations often continue to decrease for about two weeks after cases plateau. This is tough, but I'm going to increase my post oct 4 probability a bit.

10-day average of 46.6 less hospitalizations per day puts the 2,500 mark at October 3rd, remarkably close to the beginning of the final bucket. The 5-day average is down to 43.2 less per day (2,500 on October 5th), meaning the average is still decreasing since my last forecast just 4 days ago (September 27th and October 2nd, respectively). Looking at the actual plot, it is fairly easy to see that the hospitalizations are beginning to level out. The question now is whether the descent will continue at its current rate, speed up, slow down, or reverse. A complete reverse is unlikely in just a few weeks, as is an increase given current behaviors. Most likely, on average, the rate will continue to decrease in the next few weeks, which makes the final bucket the most likely. Random fluctuations and the potential for a sudden drop does leave a decent chance that the fourth bucket ends up winning.

Averaging three different approaches: 1) With an average number like yesterdays decrease (52, which was a little lower than the average of the week before) we would be at 2500 by 29 September with a linear approach. (80:20) 2) If we view it as asymtotic towards somewhere below 2500, it would take a little longer, which could indeed lead to bin 5. (60:40) 3) If we look at the "big picture", it´s as discussed before: number of new infections is going down significantly, leading to less new hospitalizations. With the average person leaving hospital after 2-3 weeks it would be much faster, perhaps in a week already. On the other hand we need to consider the worst-case-possibility of numbers increasing again (20% for that), so it´s 80:20 for this approach).

Given no policy or social distancing changes in Texas, our prediction could be reasonably modelled with a MC simulation of daily % decreases in hospitalizations that are assumed to be normally distributed (Texas hospitalizations have been steadily decreasing since July 28th, and new daily hospital admissions have been trending down since early July). Under such a simulation, it is predicted with 99.5% probability that the next time the daily number of hospitalizations will be 2500 or lower will be between Sep. 14 and Oct. 4. There is a 0.5% probability it will be after Oct. 4.

The rate of hospitalizations has decreased by 6600 over a month and a half. At this rate, we would see less than 2500 within 2 weeks. However, there is a lot of variance about this number, skewed towards the ‘upside’ (longer than 2 weeks). The graph of hospitalizations shows a slight flattening more recently in the trend. Given the trend doesn’t continue, I think the number of hospitalizations may continue to be above 2500 for quite a while; even before cases spiked in Texas, hospitalizations averaged around 1700 for several months. This number serves as a level of ‘irreducible’ hospitalizations that are simply too hard/expensive to control. 2500 is not much higher than this ‘irreducible’ level, again increasing the size of that right tail. California has had a similar (https://update.covid19.ca.gov/) growth and decline, and seems to be getting close to the ‘irreducible’ level with no sign of slowing down.

I exported the hospitalization data for New York and found that the log of hospitalization numbers declines linearly with time. Using New York as an analog, Texas will fall below 2500 on Sep 25th. However, Texas does not have any nearly as much intervention as New York, so Sep 25th is a more optimistic estimation. Using Texas' own data, the first day below 2500 is Oct 24th. Thus, the baseline probability of the bin "Between 14 September 2020 and 4 October 2020" is approximately 10/30 = 33%, and the baseline probability of "Not before 4 October 2020" is then 67%.

The main difficulty of this problem comes with the fatness of the tails. Will take a more in depth look at this problem tomorrow, but for this projection I simply looked at the % decrease in hospitalizations over the last two weeks. Average decline over the past 2 weeks has been -2.6% a day, however over the past week we have only averaged a -1.4% decline per day. Again, because the tails are fatter this -1.4% decline seems to be a more likely rate, and potentially even something less than that (as declining rates have been even smaller in the past few days.

Baseline: To create our baseline we read in the data and looked at how the hospitalization trends have developed so far and if there are predictors that can be used as leading indicators. We see that using an AR (autoregressive) model, we can use the number of positive test cases as a leading indicator to see what the hospitalization rates will look like in the future. We see that values are lagging by 7-10 days, which is in line with CDC guidelines regarding the virus. Furthermore, we also modeled with a Monte Carlo simulation using the previous log growth values and a normal distribution for the decreases from historical values.

I fitted an AR(17) model after testing for autocorrelation. The EV is Sept 30, 2020 based on my model. However, given the asymptotic behavior of the number of hospitalizations, the fact that my EV is closer to October 4 than September 13 and the fact that COVID cases could spike back up with the coming on fall/winter and the reopening of the economy, I put more weight on after October 4, 2020 then between August 24, 2020 - September 13, 2020.

I used data since the number of hospitalizations in Texas started to drop in mid-July, because I don't think the kind of wave that occurred before that is likely to occur again before October 4. Specifically I used the most recent 50 data points. I then ran two Monte Carlo simulations. The sampled from percent changes in the hospitalization numbers, whereas the second sampled from arithmetic changes. I averaged these numbers to obtain the final result.

Hospitalizations today were recorded at 7,216 with a downward linear trend around 183 people per day. If this trend holds, it would take 26 days to pass 2,500 hospitalizations per day, which puts us at September 6th. However, consistent linear trends are rare in epidemiology, both on the way up and on the way down. More likely, the slope will decrease in magnitude in the coming weeks (even if a second wave does not begin). This drop in magnitude will likely push the 2,500 benchmark back by several days, putting an expected date closer to the September 14th range. A lot could happen between now and then, but at least at the moment, I'd say there is a good chance we won't see less than 2500 hospitalizations in a single day in Texas until mid- to late-September.

There is an indication hospitalizations for Covid-19 has peaked in Texas as the number has been quite steady the last five days and showing a slight decrease in the last two. If 14 July was the peak it was at 10569 hospitalizations so roughly four times 2500. Coming week should make it clear if 14 July was a peak or not, I give it a probability of around 80% that it was. After New York peaked in their number of hospitalizations on 12 April with 18825 it took until 22 May, or 41 days, to get down to 1/4 of the peak number with 4642 hospitalizations. [1] 41 days from 14 July is 23 August. The ICU numbers seem to follow the same trajectory in New York with a delay of a day or two. If the same logic can be applied to Sweden we see that between the peak to when the number of patients in ICU was down to 1/4 there were 68 days.[2] 68 days from 14 July is 19 September. The pandemic seem to have had a more explosive development in New York than it has had in Texas. In New York there are 17 days from when you first hit 1/3 of the eventual peak to when you hit the peak[1], in Texas it was 24 days (assuming a peak was reached 14 July). This indicates a flatter curve which will make it take a longer time for Texas to get the numbers down. Summary and conclusion: I believe a peak has been reached in Texas the 14 of July and that it will take around 41-68 days (23 August-19 September), likely much closer to 68, to get to 2500 patients or below.
